# Load dataset
data <- read.csv("DataTrustMA.csv", na.strings = "")

# drop any empty rows
data <- data[is.na(data$Ref) == FALSE, ]

# subset to useful data
keepVars <- c("Year", "Paper", "FaceSample", "ParticipantSample", "GTOpRecode", 
    "RespMethRecode", "OverallDomain", "PhotoTypeRecode", "Point_of_Decision", 
    "UseFirstVersion", "PhotoSource", "UnitOfAnalysis", "N", "N_Stimuli", "final_r")
data <- data[, keepVars]

# subset only the rater-level effects
data <- data[data$UnitOfAnalysis == "Rater", ]

# when we do this, we end up with some retained levels within factors which
# are no longer used. We can get rid of these using droplevels():
data <- droplevels(data)

# Create table that counts the total number of each random factor. This can
# be adapted for any random factors. Note that in this example, we are using
# the 'unique' function to count the number of unique studies and species to
# avoid double counting.

get.table <- function(x) {
    stuff <- c(paste("N_studies = ", length(unique(x$Paper))), paste("N_faceSamples = ", 
        length(unique(x$FaceSample))), paste("N_participantSamples = ", length(unique(x$ParticipantSample))), 
        paste("N_ES = ", length(x$Zr)))
}

Meta-analysis

Here, we are testing whether we need to include the random factors in our meta-analysis models. We will be running likelihood ratio tests to compare models that include the random factors to the intercept-only model. We do this step by step - 1. Test each random factor separately. 2. Include the significant random factors together to see if they improve the model further. Some random factors take theoretical precedance over others. For example, Studyid is usually an important random factor.

The important stats here for the model comparison is the loglik values.

Throughout the analysis that we swtich between REML and ML in the specification of the method for the RMA models. We run REML when we want to extract parameter estimates. We run ML when we want to compare models.

# M0: model without random-effects using rma () to calculate I2
# (heterogeneity) vi = precision
res0 <- rma(yi = Zr, vi = 1/w, data = data, method = "REML")  #I^2 = 71.84%
summary(res0)
## 
## Random-Effects Model (k = 37; tau^2 estimator: REML)
##

# Get MuMIn to work with metafor (BESPOKE CODE BY MUMIN CREATOR TO WORK WITH
# METAFOR)
formula.rma.mv <- function(x, ...) return(eval(getCall(x)$mods))

makeArgs.rma.mv <- function(obj, termNames, comb, opt, ...) {
    ret <- MuMIn:::makeArgs.default(obj, termNames, comb, opt)
    names(ret)[1L] <- "mods"
    ret
}

nobs.rma.mv <- function(object, ...) attr(logLik(object), "nall")

coefTable.rma.mv <- function(model, ...) MuMIn:::.makeCoefTable(model$b, model$se, 
    coefNames = rownames(model$b))

# Get QM statistics for testing moderator significance. Basically a t stat
# for testing the significance of the moderator using the results from the
# average model and the variance stats from the full model.

# publication bias analysis with residuals metafor can extract residuals BUT
# doesnt include random factors so here we need a bayesian analysis
# (MCMCglmm) which can produce this info too

data[, "centered_year"] <- centered_year

# set up prior We define as many Gs as their are random effects.
prior1 <- list(R = list(V = 1, nu = 0.002), G = list(G1 = list(V = 1, nu = 1, 
    alpha.mu = 0, alpha.V = 1000), G2 = list(V = 1, nu = 1, alpha.mu = 0, alpha.V = 1000), 
    G3 = list(V = 1, fix = 1)))

# getting observational level random effect
data$obs <- as.factor(1:dim(data)[1])
vc_matrix <- matrix(0, nrow = dim(data)[1], ncol = dim(data)[1])

# created variance-covariance matrix
rownames(vc_matrix) <- data$obs
colnames(vc_matrix) <- data$obs

diag(vc_matrix) <- 1/data$w
is.positive.definite(vc_matrix)
## [1] TRUE
# prepared for MCMCglmm
invVC <- solve(vc_matrix)
invVC <- as(invVC, "dgCMatrix")

# NOTE! model estimation has been put in an inactive loop so that it doesn't
# need to re-run each time we run the script

if (FALSE) {
    
    
    modelMCMC <- MCMCglmm(Zr ~ centered_year, random = ~Paper + Paper:ParticipantSample + 
        obs, data = data, nitt = 13000 * 10, thin = 10 * 10, burnin = 3000 * 
        10, pr = T, ginverse = list(obs = invVC), prior = prior1)
    
    # save(modelMCMC, file = 'ModelMCMC_Rater.RData')
}


load(file = "ModelMCMC_Rater.RData")

# VCV is an automatically generated column in the model object, capturing
# estimate of random effect over iterations

# Extracting residuals

# Create predicted values from MCMCglmm model
Pred <- predict(modelMCMC, marginal = ~obs)
# Calculate residual by using the observed effect size minus the predicted
# effect size
es <- data$Zr - Pred
# Create precision values. The weight of the effect sizes based on sample
# size.
Prec <- 1/sqrt(1/data$w)  # Precision = 1/sqrt(V)

data2 <- data.frame(ES = es, Prec = Prec)

res12 <- rma(yi = es, sei = 1/Prec, method = "REML", data = data2)
summary(res12)

Supplementary analysis to check the effect of the number of raters on variance of effect sizes

# here we calculate T, which is the effect size Zr, accounting for the size
# of the N used to determine the df for that effect size. T is Zr divided by
# SE observer, sqrt(1/(N-3)) (which we can write as sqrt(1/w))
data$T_Zr <- data$Zr/(sqrt(1/data$w))

# Now we can plot T as a function of the secondary N (number of stimuli)

ggplot(data = data) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = 1/sqrt(N_Stimuli), y = T_Zr)) + 
    ggtitle("Rater Level")

# statistically test whether variance in T varies as N changes


# We're going to use 1/sqrt(N_[...]) a lot here, so let's make it its own
# variable:

data$N_Stimuli_Trans <- 1/sqrt(data$N_Stimuli)

# fit a linear regression model:
M.lm1 <- lm(T_Zr ~ N_Stimuli_Trans, data = data)

# now let's plot the residuals.  first we save the residuals into the data
# frames
data$lmResiduals <- M.lm1$residuals

# and now we can plot them:
ggplot(data = data) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = 1/sqrt(N_Stimuli), y = lmResiduals)) + 
    ggtitle("Rater Level")

# re-fit the linear models using gls so that we can compare the AIC:
M.lm <- gls(T_Zr ~ N_Stimuli_Trans, data = data)

# specify a fixed variance structure
vf1 <- varFixed(~N_Stimuli_Trans)

# fit the model with this new variance structure:
M.gls1 <- gls(T_Zr ~ N_Stimuli_Trans, weights = vf1, data = data)

# let's look at the model summaries
summary(M.lm)
